this card can be good if you use it in the right situations, its just that it doesn't really fit into the automation meta which is just to spam random functions because any function is a good function.

I've used this card with the event functions before though; but strategy like that have to be specced into in the first half of act one or your just going to find yourself defaulting back to card spam like usual.

its by no means a bad card; just one that you dont get to pick very often due to how the character tends to play. In that sense its very fitting as an X cost card as those are usually very situational.
Can you write Kotlin outputting JVM 8 bytecode or is that too crazy an idea?

I will say that if you find this card pre-upgraded, it's basically free value. Double-encode something next turn for the cost of 0 energy and one draw, with further upside on the rare occasion that you have nothing you need to spend energy on this turn.
granted, most 0-cost cards are at least that good when pre-upgraded

For loop has a delayed (usually), but very powerful effect. Since it uses up all your energy, you won't typically be able to play a strong encode card on the same turn, but you could use turbo to change that, and format/replicate allow you to immediately encode several weaker cards. If you are willing to wait until next turn, you can multiply the compile effects of boost, fortify, and repair, or just generally powerful encode cards like iterate, and goto. Runic pyramid is very helpful here to help line up one of the better encode cards with for loops effect on the next turn, and can also let you hold onto extra functions if you make more than you can play in one turn.

It's main competition is from class default, and merge conflict can also do a similar trick once. Class default has the advantage of being cheaper and having better interactions with a few key cards (constructor, digital carnage, and full release). You can more easily fit class default into a productive turn, where for loop will usually require that you put most of a full turn into it to really get value out. For loop has a pretty significant drawback, but I do think the effect is powerful enough to warrant that. 

I probably wouldn't start taking for loop unless I already had chem X (format is your only other X cost card, and is rare, so that's unlikely, but chem X is very strong with both cards), or I already had at least one of boost, fortify, or repair. For loop really shines more in acts 3 and 4, and potentially the act 2 boss. It's slow speed is a liability in hallway fights and most of the elite fights in acts 1 and 2, so try not to take it too early. The upgrade is pretty standard for an X cost card, the +1 is fine, but not really a priority, especially when you could be upgrading an encode card instead.
